    ✅orb.resolve_initial_references("RootPOA");

Important Clarification
========================
POA → hierarchical (tree)
ORB → flat (single root, no internal hierarchy)

Analogy
=======
ORB = Operating System
POA hierarchy = File system (folders/subfolders)


Show the hierarchy of POA in CORBA Java?
========================================
In CORBA (Java), the Portable Object Adapter (POA) is organized in a hierarchical structure that 
manages object lifecycles, request processing, and servant activation.

Here’s the hierarchy in a clear way:

POA Hierarchy in CORBA
======================
ORB (Object Request Broker)
   │
   └── RootPOA
          │
          ├── Child POA (POA1)
          │       ├── Grandchild POA (POA1_1)
          │       └── Grandchild POA (POA1_2)
          │
          └── Child POA (POA2)
                  └── Grandchild POA (POA2_1)

Explanation of Each Level
=========================
1. ORB (Object Request Broker)
The top-level runtime that handles communication between client and server.
All POAs exist under the ORB.

2. RootPOA
The default POA created automatically when the ORB starts.
Acts as the root of the POA hierarchy.
Provides basic policies and acts as a parent for all other POAs.

3. Child POAs

Created using:

POA childPOA = rootPOA.create_POA("POA1", manager, policies);
Each child POA:
Inherits behavior from its parent
Can define its own policies (lifespan, threading, servant retention, etc.)

4. Grandchild (Nested) POAs
POAs can be nested to any depth
Useful for:
Separating object groups
Applying different policies
Managing scalability

Key Characteristics of POA Hierarchy
====================================
Tree structure (not a graph)
Each POA has exactly one parent
Policies are independent but inherited contextually
Helps organize:
Object activation
Request routing
Servant management

Example (Java CORBA)
====================
ORB orb = ORB.init(args, null);

// Get RootPOA
POA rootPOA = POAHelper.narrow(
    orb.resolve_initial_references("RootPOA")
);

// Create child POA
POA childPOA = rootPOA.create_POA(
    "ChildPOA",
    rootPOA.the_POAManager(),
    null
);

Why This Hierarchy Matters
==========================
Enables modular design
Allows different policies per POA
Improves scalability and control
Supports fine-grained object management


